The above described and many other features and attendant advantages of the present invention will become apparent from a consideration of the following detailed description when considered in conjunction with the accompanying drawings.


BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF THE DRAWINGS


FIG. 1 is a perspective view showing the front wheel of a cycle disposed in the chock/cradle apparatus, prior to association of the dolly with such apparatus;


FIG. 2 is a front elevational view of the dolly, showing it in collapsed condition ready for carrying by the operator;


FIG. 3 is a view corresponding to FIG. 2 but showing the dolly after it has been made ready for use, by lowering the wheels to the ground;


FIG. 4 corresponds to FIG. 3 but shows the central portion of the dolly elevated;


FIG. 5 is a top plan view of the showing of FIG. 7, but with no cycle wheel;


FIG. 6 is an isometric view of the central part of the dolly;


FIG. 7 is a view showing the cycle wheel supported in the dolly;


FIG. 8 is an isometric view illustrating the rotatable trunnion lock;


FIG. 9 is a view of the sliding chock retaining pin engaged in chock/cradle elements;


FIG. 10 is a side elevational view of the front portion of the cycle in condition for wheeling to a desired position such as a ramp leading to the bed of a tow truck;


FIG. 11 is a sectional view showing lock mechanism for the dolly;


FIG. 12 is a perspective view of another embodiment of the present invention showing the front wheel of a cycle secured to another chock/cradle embodiment apparatus raised off of the floor;


FIG. 13 is another perspective view corresponding to FIG. 12 with the dolly in a collapsed condition ready for carrying by the operator;


FIG. 14 is yet another perspective view corresponding to FIG. 12, with the arms of the dolly in the extended position;


FIG. 15 is still another perspective view of the chock/cradle apparatus corresponding to FIG. 12 without the wheel from a cycle secured to the chock/cradle apparatus;


FIG. 16 is a cross-sectional view of the front and rear chocks along the line 16--16 in FIG. 14;


FIG. 17 is a close up view of the dolly around the shaft area corresponding to FIG. 13;


FIG. 18 is a side view of the dolly around the shaft area corresponding to FIG. 13;


FIG. 19 is a cross-sectional view of an outrigger bar along the line 19--19 in FIG. 15, along with a clip to facilitate attaching a ratcheting strap to the end of the outrigger bar;


FIG. 20 is a side view of an exemplary clip; and


FIG. 21 is a side view showing the front and back wheels of a cycle secured to a pair chock/cradle apparatuses, respectively, to raise the front and back wheels off of the floor.
